It is often the practice in will construction suits for beneficiaries in the same interest to have joint representation. Normally this will be a matter of consent between them. However, the present rule authorises the making of a representative order in appropriate cases. Sometimes it may occur that a trustee company is involved in different interests in the proceedings. Since no party can appear in more than one interest (subject to the qualification in 
r 6.18
), the usual practice is to appoint the company's manager, or other senior officer, to represent one of the relevant interests. Where there is no party willing to put arguments on behalf of an interest, the court may either require the appointment of a representative or invite counsel for a trustee plaintiff to put forward such arguments.
